<br>
Do we need more space?  Whats wrong with earth-orbiting (or solar-orbiting) stations?<br>
<br>
Are there (valuable) minerals in abundance enough to make a mining operation feasible?  If not, what is the impetus to land on a solid surface with gravity to escape from?<br>
<br>
I understand mars, to certain extent.  If a comet were smashed into one of the poles, it might be made habitable in a couple hundred years (read the Millenial project, mentioned earlier.). Further, mars is a non-homogenous body (I think the moon is pretty homogenous) with large possibilities for water, minerals and ore.  I believe that it would be feasible for a mars colony to eventually become self-sufficient.  I dont see that happening on the moon.  IMO, The Millenial Foundation is a little off in their analysis of the moon situation.  Maybe I'm wrong.  Please Inform me! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 114<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/8/02 10:16:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Moonbase</span><hr size=1> There is water on the moon, as well as oxygen. Those are the primary components to getting a self-sustaining planet. The advantage to a moon base is it's ability to have a gravitational force, while still being seporate from the earth. One can do quite a bit of research there that is impossible on earth and difficult in space, not to mention the ability to stay longer due to gravitational forces being in play, and others. It's much closer than mars, and although somewhat more expensive, it is acheivable. It would make a great base for launching missions beyond the moon/earth. I think this should help with the idea somewhat. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1778<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 12:59:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Moonbase</span><hr size=1> We are rather lucky to have such an exceptionally large moon. Saturn and Jupiter have dozens of them but few come close to the size of Luna. One sixth Earth gravity should be enough to keep the blood pumping and muscles/bone from degenerating too much. Lengthy stays and even possibly colonisation are feasible. Would make an interesting place to play golf. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 171<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/17/02 2:16:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Zero G sports &amp; living</span><hr size=1> I wrote earlier about Savage's domed crater colonies.<br>
