about this.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I've read a lot on it. I still wonder what the moon's good for. I still value the science it offers, as well as the wanderlust of humans. We will want to open it up.<br>
<br>
 Other than that (long term, when we can afford extravagances), not much.<br>
 Though there's water on the Moon, it's easier to get to &amp; from an NEA with vastly better resources and lower required Delta-V.<br>
 As well as being harder to reach because of its gravity  the Moon is called the slagpile of the solar system because the best ores we've found on the moon are about like the tailings an asteroid miner would toss out as not economic to process further. Sure, there may be deposits of highly valuable ores, but asteroids are flying mountains and islands varying from 90% metallic chunks to loose aglomerations which are 40% ices.<br>
 A good way to look at it is that the same level of effort &amp; investment to put in a base on the Moon would return less useful things than an equal investment spent on asteroid retrieval. The asteroid effort would return more resources of a better grade in the same time as the Lunar mine, with more room for advancement.<br>
<br>
 There most definately are valuable resources there, but there's even more than the Moon floating out there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &gt; Do we need more space?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Well, yes we do, along with resources.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &gt; Whats wrong with earth-orbiting (or solar-orbiting) stations?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 We need space colonies because they gain us more &quot;space&quot; -as in area &amp; resources for people to live- in free space settlements than settlements on planets.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &gt; what is the impetus to land on a solid surface with gravity<br>
to escape from?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Planetary Chauvanism. The illusion that we'll always live predominantly on planets and other large space bodies because that's the way every human who's ever lived, has lived.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Space settlement is a unique concept for colonization beyond the Earth.  While most thinking regarding the expansion of the human race outward into space has focused on the colonization of the surfaces of other planets, thespace settlement concept suggests that planetary surfaces may not be the best location for extraterrestrial colonies.  Artificial, closed-ecology habitats in free orbit would seem to have many advantages over any planetary home (Earth included).</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://members.aol.com/oscarcombs/puzzle.htm"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.aol.com/oscarcombs/puzzle.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Clarke wrote that looking back from far in the future, it'll be seen that for most of human history, the word &quot;ship&quot; will mean &quot;space ship&quot;.<br>
<br>
Terraforming Mars is an astonishingly huge project for relatively small return, looking from the long-term. For more living area, Mars adds about as much surface area as the entire land area of Earth. Presumeably, making it livable would mean adding oceans, which on Earth take up 75% of the global surface area.<br>
Taking only the nearby, short-orbit asteroids &amp; comets apart and building space colonies provides several thousand times the living area and resources as the Earth's surface. Long before Mars is livable, we'd have had more, better additional living room in space colonies.<br>
<br>
